Load the data

These data are a modified version of the Statlog (Heart) database on heart disease from the UCI Machine Learning Repository. The data are also available on Kaggle.

You will need the descriptions of the variables to answer the questions. Please reference 03_midterm2_descriptions.Rmd for details.

Run the following to load the data.

heart <- read_csv("data/heart.csv")

Problem 2. (1 point) Let’s explore the demographics of participants included in the study. What is the number of males and females? Show this as a table. There were 87 females and 183 males sampled.

heart %>% 
  group_by(gender) %>% 
  summarize(n_gender = n())
## # A tibble: 2 × 2
##   gender n_gender
##   <chr>     <int>
## 1 female       87
## 2 male        183

Problem 3. (2 points) What is the average age of participants by gender? Show this as a table. Females sampled had an average age of 55.68 years and males sampled had an average age of 53.84 years.

heart %>% 
  group_by(gender) %>% 
  summarize(average_age_gender = mean(age, na.rm = T))

Problem 4. (1 point) Among males and females, how many have/do not have heart disease? Show this as a table, grouped by gender. 20 of the females sampled have heart disease while 67 do not. 100 of the males sampled have heart disease while 83 do not.

heart %>% 
  group_by(gender, target) %>% 
  summarize(status_gender = n(), .groups = 'keep')
## # A tibble: 4 × 3
## # Groups:   gender, target [4]
##   gender target     status_gender
##   <chr>  <chr>              <int>
## 1 female disease               20
## 2 female no_disease            67
## 3 male   disease              100
## 4 male   no_disease            83

Problem 5. (4 points) What is the percentage of males and females with heart disease? Show this as a table, grouped by gender. 22.99% of females sampled have heart disease while 54.64% of males sampled have heart disease.

heart_percent <- heart %>% 
  group_by(gender, target) %>% 
  summarize(status_gender = n(), .groups = 'keep') %>% 
  pivot_wider(names_from = target,
              values_from = status_gender) %>% 
  mutate(percent_heart_disease = (100*(disease/(disease+no_disease))))
heart_percent
## # A tibble: 2 × 4
## # Groups:   gender [2]
##   gender disease no_disease percent_heart_disease
##   <chr>    <int>      <int>                 <dbl>
## 1 female      20         67                  23.0
## 2 male       100         83                  54.6

Problem 6. (3 points) Make a plot that shows the results of your analysis from problem 5. If you couldn’t get the percentages to work, then make a plot that shows the number of participants with and without heart disease by gender.

heart_percent %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = gender, y = percent_heart_disease, fill = gender))+
  geom_col(color = "black", alpha = 0.5)+
  theme_stata()+
  labs(title = "Percentage of Individuals with Heart Disease by Gender", x  = "Gender", y = "% with heart disease")

Problem 7. (3 points) Is there a relationship between age and cholesterol levels? Make a plot that shows this relationship separated by gender (hint: use faceting or make two plots). Be sure to add a line of best fit (linear regression line). There appears to be a slight positive relationship between age and cholesterol levels in this sample. This trend appears to be stronger in females than in males.

heart %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = age, y = chol))+
  geom_point()+
  geom_smooth(method = lm, se = F, color = "orange")+
  facet_wrap(~gender, ncol = 2)+
  theme_stata()+
  labs(title = "Age vs Cholesterol Levels for Males and Females Sampled", x = "Age", y = "Sampled Cholesterol Levels")
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

Problem 8. (3 points) What is the range of resting blood pressure for participants by type of chest pain? Make a plot that shows this information.

heart %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = cp, y = trestbps))+
  geom_boxplot(fill = "wheat", alpha = 0.5)+
  theme_stata()+
  labs(title = "Ranges of Resting Blood Pressure by Chest Pain Classification", x = "Chest Pain Classification", y = "Resting Blood Pressure")

Problem 9. (4 points) What is the distribution of maximum heart rate achieved, separated by gender and whether or not the patient has heart disease? Make a plot that shows this information- you must use faceting.

heart %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = thalach))+
  geom_density(fill = "wheat", alpha = 0.5)+
  facet_grid(gender~target)+
  theme_stata()+
  labs(title = "Distribution of Maximum Heart Rate by Disease Status and Gender", x = "Maximum Heart Rate", y = "Density")

Problem 10. (4 points) What is the range of ST depression (oldpeak) by the number of major vessels colored by fluoroscopy (ca)? Make a plot that shows this relationship. (hint: should ca be a factor or numeric variable?)

heart %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = as.factor(ca), y = oldpeak))+
  geom_boxplot(fill = "wheat", alpha = 0.5)+
  theme_stata()+
  labs(title = "Range of ST Depression by # of Major Vessels Colored by Fluoroscopy", x = "# of major vessels colored by fluoroscopy", y = "ST depression")

Problem 11. (4 points) Is there an age group where we see increased prevalence of heart disease? Make a plot that shows the number of participants with and without heart disease by age group. There appears to be an increased prevalence of heart disease in the 55-61 age group, which was the group ranging from the median to the 3rd quartile. I produced age groups that matched the 1st, 2nd, 3rd, and 4th quartiles for age.

summary(heart$age)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##   29.00   48.00   55.00   54.43   61.00   77.00
heart %>% 
  mutate(age_group = case_when(age <= 48 ~ "29-48",
                               age > 48 & age <= 55 ~ "48-55",
                               age > 55 & age <= 61 ~ "55-61",
                               age > 61 ~ "61-77")) %>%
  group_by(age_group, target) %>% 
  summarize(status_age_group = n(), .groups = 'keep') %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = age_group, y = status_age_group, fill = target))+
  geom_col(pos = "dodge", color = "black", alpha = 0.5)+
  theme_stata()+
  labs(title = "# of Participants With or Without Heart Disease by Age Group", x = "Age Group", y = "Count")
